    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1855-04-25T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1855-04-25T00:00:00-05:00" n="145"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d145">
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">Mr. <persName type="from">Cushing</persName>,
                        Attorney-General, to Mr. <persName type="to">McKeon</persName>, district
                        attorney.</hi>
                </head>
                <dateline>
                    <placeName>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Attorney-General’s Office</hi>
                    </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1855-04-25">
                        <hi rend="italic">April</hi> 25, 1855</date>.</dateline>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: The Secretary of State having referred me to your
                    letter of the 24th instant, with its inclosures, I have taken the directions of
                    the President on the subject, and in accordance therewith have to request you to
                    institute legal proceedings against *Colonel Kinney and the steamer United
                    States, provided, in, your judgment, the evidence accessible will suffice to
                    afford probable cause. <seg type="margin">[179]</seg>
                </p>
                <p>I have the honor to be, &amp;c., &amp;c.,</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>C. CUSHING.</signed>
                </closer>
                <postscript>
                    <p>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">John McKeon</hi>, Esq.,<lb/>
                        <hi rend="italic">United States District Attorney, New York.</hi>
                    </p>
                    <p>P. S.—Since writing the above, I have seen the letter of Mr. Fabens in the
                        New York Herald of yesterday, which seems to require that he be proceeded
                        against equally with Colonel Kenney.</p>
                    <closer>
                        <signed>C. C.</signed>
                    </closer>
                </postscript>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
